# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lowest-common-ancestor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] In computer science, a **Cartesian tree** is a binary tree derived from a sequence of distinct numbers.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] To construct the Cartesian tree, set its root to be the minimum number in the sequence, and recursively construct its left and right subtrees from the subsequences before and after this number.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] It is uniquely defined as a min-heap whose symmetric (in-order) traversal returns the original sequence.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Cartesian trees were introduced by Vuillemin (1980) in the context of geometric range searching data structures.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] They have also been used in the definition of the treap and randomized binary search tree data structures for binary search problems, in comparison sort algorithms that perform efficiently on nearly-sorted inputs, and as the basis for pattern matching algorithms.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] A Cartesian tree for a sequence can be constructed in linear time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Cartesian trees are defined using binary trees, which are a form of rooted tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] To construct the Cartesian tree for a given sequence of distinct numbers, set its root to be the minimum number in the sequence, and recursively construct its left and right subtrees from the subsequences before and after this number, respectively.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] As a base case, when one of these subsequences is empty, there is no left or right child.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] It is also possible to characterize the Cartesian tree directly rather than recursively, using its ordering properties.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] In any tree, the *subtree* rooted at any node consists of all other nodes that can reach it by repeatedly following parent pointers.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] A symmetric (in-order) traversal of the tree results in the original sequence.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Equivalently, for each node, the numbers in its left subtree are earlier than it in the sequence, and the numbers in the right subtree are later.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The tree has the min-heap property: the parent of any non-root node has a smaller value than the node itself.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] These two definitions are equivalent: the tree defined recursively as described above is the unique tree that has the properties listed above.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] If a sequence of numbers contains repetitions, a Cartesian tree can be determined for it by following a consistent tie-breaking rule before applying the above construction.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] For instance, the first of two equal elements can be treated as the smaller of the two.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Cartesian trees were introduced and named by Vuillemin (1980), who used them as an example of the interaction between geometric combinatorics and the design and analysis of data structures.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] In particular, Vuillemin used these structures to analyze the average-case complexity of concatenation and splitting operations on binary search trees.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Vuillemin described both this geometric version of the structure, and the definition here in which a Cartesian tree is defined from a sequence.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Using sequences instead of point coordinates provides a more general setting that allows the Cartesian tree to be applied to non-geometric problems as well.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] A Cartesian tree can be constructed in linear time from its input sequence.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] One method is to process the sequence values in left-to-right order, maintaining the Cartesian tree of the nodes processed so far, in a structure that allows both upwards and downwards traversal of the tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] To process each new value a , start at the node representing the value prior to a in the sequence and follow the path from this node to the root of the tree until finding a value b smaller than a .
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The node a becomes the right child of b , and the previous right child of b becomes the new left child of a .
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The total time for this procedure is linear, because the time spent searching for the parent b of each new node a can be charged against the number of nodes that are removed from the rightmost path in the tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] An alternative linear-time construction algorithm is based on the all nearest smaller values problem.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] In the input sequence, define the *left neighbor* of a value a to be the value that occurs prior to a , is smaller than a , and is closer in position to a than any other smaller value.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The *right neighbor* is defined symmetrically.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The sequence of left neighbors can be found by an algorithm that maintains a stack containing a subsequence of the input.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] For each new sequence value a , the stack is popped until it is empty or its top element is smaller than a , and then a is pushed onto the stack.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The left neighbor of a is the top element at the time a is pushed.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The right neighbors can be found by applying the same stack algorithm to the reverse of the sequence.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The parent of a in the Cartesian tree is either the left neighbor of a or the right neighbor of a , whichever exists and has a larger value.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The left and right neighbors can also be constructed efficiently by parallel algorithms, making this formulation useful in efficient parallel algorithms for Cartesian tree construction.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Another linear-time algorithm for Cartesian tree construction is based on divide-and-conquer.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The algorithm recursively constructs the tree on each half of the input, and then merges the two trees.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The merger process involves only the nodes on the left and right *spines* of these trees: the left spine is the path obtained by following left child edges from the root until reaching a node with no left child, and the right spine is defined symmetrically.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] As with any path in a min-heap, both spines have their values in sorted order, from the smallest value at their root to their largest value at the end of the path.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] To merge the two trees, apply a merge algorithm to the right spine of the left tree and the left spine of the right tree, replacing these two paths in two trees by a single path that contains the same nodes.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] In the merged path, the successor in the sorted order of each node from the left tree is placed in its right child, and the successor of each node from the right tree is placed in its left child, the same position that was previously used for its successor in the spine.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The left children of nodes from the left tree and right children of nodes from the right tree remain unchanged.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The algorithm is parallelizable since on each level of recursion, each of the two sub-problems can be computed in parallel, and the merging operation can be efficiently parallelized as well.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] This element is then removed from the list, and attached as the right child of its left neighbor, or the left child of its right neighbor, depending on which of the two neighbors has a larger value, breaking ties arbitrarily.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] This process can be implemented in a single left-to-right pass of the input, and it is easy to see that each element can gain at most one left-, and at most one right child, and that the resulting binary tree is a Cartesian tree of the input sequence.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] It is possible to maintain the Cartesian tree of a dynamic input, subject to insertions of elements and lazy deletion of elements, in logarithmic amortized time per operation.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Here, lazy deletion means that a deletion operation is performed by marking an element in the tree as being a deleted element, but not actually removing it from the tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] When the number of marked elements reaches a constant fraction of the size of the whole tree, it is rebuilt, keeping only its unmarked elements.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Cartesian trees form part of an efficient data structure for range minimum queries.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] An input to this kind of query specifies a contiguous subsequence of the original sequence; the query output should be the minimum value in this subsequence.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] In a Cartesian tree, this minimum value can be found at the lowest common ancestor of the leftmost and rightmost values in the subsequence.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] For instance, in the subsequence (12,10,20,15,18) of the example sequence, the minimum value of the subsequence (10) forms the lowest common ancestor of the leftmost and rightmost values (12 and 18).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Because lowest common ancestors can be found in constant time per query, using a data structure that takes linear space to store and can be constructed in linear time, the same bounds hold for the range minimization problem.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Bender & Farach-Colton (2000) reversed this relationship between the two data structure problems by showing that data structures for range minimization could also be used for finding lowest common ancestors.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Their data structure associates with each node of the tree its distance from the root, and constructs a sequence of these distances in the order of an Euler tour of the (edge-doubled) tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] It then constructs a range minimization data structure for the resulting sequence.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The lowest common ancestor of any two vertices in the given tree can be found as the minimum distance appearing in the interval between the initial positions of these two vertices in the sequence.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Bender and Farach-Colton also provide a method for range minimization that can be used for the sequences resulting from this transformation, which have the special property that adjacent sequence values differ by one.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The same range minimization problem may also be given an alternative interpretation in terms of two dimensional range searching.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] A collection of finitely many points in the Cartesian plane can be used to form a Cartesian tree, by sorting the points by their x -coordinates and using the y -coordinates in this order as the sequence of values from which this tree is formed.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] In this way, after the leftmost and rightmost points in the slab are identified, all points within the three-sided region can be listed in constant time per point.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The same construction, of lowest common ancestors in a Cartesian tree, makes it possible to construct a data structure with linear space that allows the distances between pairs of points in any ultrametric space to be queried in constant time per query.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The distance within an ultrametric is the same as the minimax path weight in the minimum spanning tree of the metric.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] From the minimum spanning tree, one can construct a Cartesian tree, the root node of which represents the heaviest edge of the minimum spanning tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Removing this edge partitions the minimum spanning tree into two subtrees, and Cartesian trees recursively constructed for these two subtrees form the children of the root node of the Cartesian tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The leaves of the Cartesian tree represent points of the metric space, and the lowest common ancestor of two leaves in the Cartesian tree is the heaviest edge between those two points in the minimum spanning tree, which has weight equal to the distance between the two points.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Once the minimum spanning tree has been found and its edge weights sorted, the Cartesian tree can be constructed in linear time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The Cartesian tree of a sorted sequence is just a path graph, rooted at its leftmost endpoint.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Binary searching in this tree degenerates to sequential search in the path.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] However, a different construction uses Cartesian trees to generate binary search trees of logarithmic depth from sorted sequences of values.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] This can be done by generating *priority* numbers for each value, and using the sequence of priorities to generate a Cartesian tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] This construction may equivalently be viewed in the geometric framework described above, in which the x -coordinates of a set of points are the values in a sorted sequence and the y -coordinates are their priorities.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] This idea was applied by Seidel & Aragon (1996), who suggested the use of random numbers as priorities.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The self-balancing binary search tree resulting from this random choice is called a treap, due to its combination of binary search tree and min-heap features.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Random binary search trees have been studied for much longer than treaps, and are known to behave well as search trees.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The expected length of the search path to any given value is at most $2\ln n$ , and the whole tree has logarithmic depth (its maximum root-to-leaf distance) with high probability.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] More formally, there exists a constant C such that the depth is $\leq C\ln n$ with probability tending to one as the number of nodes tends to infinity.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The same good behavior carries over to treaps.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] It is also possible, as suggested by Aragon and Seidel, to reprioritize frequently-accessed nodes, causing them to move towards the root of the treap and speeding up future accesses for the same keys.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Levcopoulos & Petersson (1989) describe a sorting algorithm based on Cartesian trees.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] They describe the algorithm as based on a tree with the maximum at the root, but it can be modified straightforwardly to support a Cartesian tree with the convention that the minimum value is at the root.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] For consistency, it is this modified version of the algorithm that is described below.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The Levcopoulos–Petersson algorithm can be viewed as a version of selection sort or heap sort that maintains a priority queue of candidate minima, and that at each step finds and removes the minimum value in this queue, moving this value to the end of an output sequence.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] In their algorithm, the priority queue consists only of elements whose parent in the Cartesian tree has already been found and removed.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] As Levcopoulos and Petersson show, for input sequences that are already nearly sorted, the size of the priority queue will remain small, allowing this method to take advantage of the nearly-sorted input and run more quickly.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] They also prove a lower bound stating that, for any n and (non-constant) k , any comparison-based sorting algorithm must use $\Omega (n\log k)$ comparisons for some inputs.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] The problem of *Cartesian tree matching* has been defined as a generalized form of string matching in which one seeks a substring (or in some cases, a subsequence) of a given string that has a Cartesian tree of the same form as a given pattern.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/cartesian-tree] Fast algorithms for variations of the problem with a single pattern or multiple patterns have been developed, as well as data structures analogous to the suffix tree and other text indexing structures.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] In graph theory and theoretical computer science, the **level ancestor problem** is the problem of preprocessing a given rooted tree *T* into a data structure that can determine the ancestor of a given node at a given distance from the root of the tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] More precisely, let *T* be a rooted tree with *n* nodes, and let *v* be an arbitrary node of *T*.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] The level ancestor query LA(*v*,*d*) requests the ancestor of node *v* at depth *d*, where the depth of a node *v* in a tree is the number of edges on the shortest path from the root of the tree to node *v*.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] It is possible to solve this problem in constant time per query, after a preprocessing algorithm that takes O(*n*) and that builds a data structure that uses O(*n*) storage space.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] The jump pointer algorithm pre-processes a tree in O(*n* log *n*) time and answers level ancestor queries in O(log *n*) time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] The jump pointer algorithm associates up to log *n* pointers to each vertex of the tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] These pointers are called jump pointers because they jump up the tree towards the root of the tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] For a given node *v* of a tree, the algorithm stores an array of length l jumpers where $\ell =\lfloor \log _{2}(\operatorname {depth} (v))\rfloor$ .
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] The *i*th element of this array points to the 2*i*th ancestor of *v*.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] Using such data structure helps us jump halfway up the tree from any given node.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] When the algorithm is asked to process a query, we repeatedly jump up the tree using these pointers.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] The number of jumps will be at most log *n* and therefore queries can be answered in log *n* time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] The ladder algorithm is based on the idea of simplifying a tree into a collection of paths.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] The reason for this is the fact that paths are easier to be queried when it comes to level ancestor queries.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] Consider a path P consisting of n nodes rooted at a node r.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] We can store the path into an array of size n called Ladder and we can quickly answer a level ancestor query of LA(v, d) by returning Ladder[d] if depth(v)≤d.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] However, this will only work if the given tree is a path.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] Otherwise, we need to decompose it into paths.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] This is done in two stages: long-path decomposition and extending the long paths into ladders.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] This is a recursive method that decomposes a given tree into paths.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] This stages starts off by finding the longest root-to-leaf path in the tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] It then removes this path by breaking its ties from the tree which will break the remaining of the tree into sub-trees and then it recursively processes each sub-tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] Every time a path is decomposed, an array is created in association with the path that contains the elements on the path from the root to the leaf.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] The base case of this recursion is when the tree is a path in which case its removal leaves an empty graph.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] Each vertex v has a unique ladder which is the ladder containing it and we call it the "v's ladder".
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] However, after this pre-processing stage, the queries cannot be answered quickly.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] In fact in order to answer a level ancestor query, the algorithm needs to jump from a path to another until it reaches the root and there could be Θ(√*n*) of such paths on a leaf-to-root path.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] This leads us to an algorithm that can pre-process the tree in O(*n*) time and answers queries in O(√*n*).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] In order to reach the optimal query time, we need to process the results in a second stage described below.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] The first stage of the algorithm decomposes the tree into a number of disjoint paths.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] In the second stage of the algorithm, each path is extended and therefore the resulting paths will not be mutually exclusive.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] In the first stage of the algorithm, each path is associated with an array of size *h'*.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] We extend this path by adding the *h'* immediate ancestors at the top of the path in the same array.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] This will extend each array twice its original size at most which will result in *2n* total number of nodes in all the ladders.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] Notice that the number of ladders is not changed and each node's ladder remains the same.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] Although a node v can be listed in multiple paths now but its ladder is the one that was associated to v in the first stage of the algorithm.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] These two stages can be processed in O(*n*) time but the query time is not constant yet.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] Consider a level ancestor query on a node u of height h.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] By travelling to the top of u's ladder, a vertex of height at least *2h* will be reached.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] Observe that all the nodes have a height of at least 1 and therefore after doing this i times, we reach a node of height at least 2i and therefore we need to do this at most log *n* times.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] This gives us a query time of O(log *n*).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] It turns out that the ladder algorithm does not do the trick on its own.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] In fact the jump pointer algorithm and the ladder algorithm complement one another.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] The two algorithms work in opposite directions: the jump pointer algorithm makes exponentially decreasing hops and the ladder algorithm makes exponentially increasing hops.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] A combination of the two algorithms can answer queries in O(*1*) time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] A single jump pointer takes any query at least halfway up the tree after which climbing up only one ladder will answer the query.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] This results in O(*n* log *n*) pre-processing time and O(*1*) query time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] A different solution is due to Berkman and Vishkin.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] This solution is based on the Euler tour technique for processing trees.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] The main observation is that LA(*v*,*d*) is the first node of depth *d* that appears in the Euler tour after the last appearance of *v*.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] Thus, by constructing the Euler tour and associated information on depth, the problem is reduced to a query on arrays, named *find smaller* (FS).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] An efficient solution to the FS problem is hard in general, but easier for the special case that arises from Euler tours; in this case, adjacent elements differ by ±1.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] This idea yields O(1) query time, with a preprocessing algorithm of complexity O(*n* log *n*).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/level-ancestor-problem] The preprocessing time is improved to O(*n*) by an application of the Method of Four Russians.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] The LCA of v and w in T is the shared ancestor of v and w that is located farthest from the root.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] In a tree data structure where each node points to its parent, the lowest common ancestor can be easily determined by finding the first intersection of the paths from v and w to the root.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] In general, the computational time required for this algorithm is O(h) where h is the height of the tree (length of longest path from a leaf to the root).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] However, there exist several algorithms for processing trees so that lowest common ancestors may be found more quickly.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Tarjan's off-line lowest common ancestors algorithm, for example, preprocesses a tree in linear time to provide constant-time LCA queries.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] In general DAGs, similar algorithms exist, but with super-linear complexity.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] The lowest common ancestor problem was defined by Alfred Aho, John Hopcroft, and Jeffrey Ullman (1973), but Dov Harel and Robert Tarjan (1984) were the first to develop an optimally efficient lowest common ancestor data structure.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Their algorithm processes any tree in linear time, using a heavy path decomposition, so that subsequent lowest common ancestor queries may be answered in constant time per query.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] However, their data structure is complex and difficult to implement.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Tarjan also found a simpler but less efficient algorithm, based on the union-find data structure, for computing lowest common ancestors of an offline batch of pairs of nodes.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Baruch Schieber and Uzi Vishkin (1988) simplified the data structure of Harel and Tarjan, leading to an implementable structure with the same asymptotic preprocessing and query time bounds.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] The structure of Schieber and Vishkin decomposes any tree into a collection of paths, such that the connections between the paths have the structure of a binary tree, and combines both of these two simpler indexing techniques.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Omer Berkman and Uzi Vishkin (1993) discovered a completely new way to answer lowest common ancestor queries, again achieving linear preprocessing time with constant query time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] They then handle this range minimum query problem (RMQ) by combining two techniques, one technique based on precomputing the answers to large intervals that have sizes that are powers of two, and the other based on table lookup for small-interval queries.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] This method was later presented in a simplified form by Michael Bender and Martin Farach-Colton (2000).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] As had been previously observed by Gabow, Bentley & Tarjan (1984), the range minimum problem can in turn be transformed back into a lowest common ancestor problem using the technique of Cartesian trees.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Further simplifications were made by Alstrup et al.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Sleator and Tarjan (1983) proposed the dynamic LCA variant of the problem in which the data structure should be prepared to handle LCA queries intermixed with operations that change the tree (that is, rearrange the tree by adding and removing edges).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] This variant can be solved in $O(\log N)$ time in the total size of the tree for all modifications and queries.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] This is done by maintaining the forest using the dynamic trees data structure with partitioning by size; this then maintains a heavy-light decomposition of each tree, and allows LCA queries to be carried out in logarithmic time in the size of the tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] As mentioned above, LCA can be reduced to RMQ.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] An efficient solution to the resulting RMQ problem starts by partitioning the number sequence into blocks.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Two different techniques are used for queries across blocks and within blocks.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Reduction of LCA to RMQ starts by walking the tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] For each node visited, record in sequence its label and depth.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Suppose nodes *x* and *y* occur in positions *i* and *j* in this sequence, respectively.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Then the LCA of *x* and *y* will be found in position RMQ(*i*, *j*), where the RMQ is taken over the depth values.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Despite that there exists a constant time and linear space solution for general RMQ, but a simplified solution can be applied that make uses of LCA’s properties.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] This simplified solution can only be used for RMQ reduced from LCA.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Similar to the solution mentioned above, we divide the sequence into each block $B_{i}$ , where each block $B_{i}$ has size of $b={1 \over 2}\log n$ .
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] To answer the $RMQ(i,j)$ query in case one, there are 3 groups of variables precomputed to help reduce query time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] First, the minimum element with the smallest index in each block $B_{i}$ is precomputed and denoted as $y_{i}$ .
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Second, given the set of $y_{i}$ , the RMQ query for this set is precomputed using the solution with constant time and linearithmic space.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] There are $n/b$ blocks, so the lookup table in that solution takes $O({n \over b}\log {n \over b})$ space.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Hence, the precomputed RMQ query using the solution with constant time and linearithmic space on these blocks only take $O(n)$ space.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Third, in each block $B_{i}$ , let $k_{i}$ be an index in $B_{i}$ such that $0\leq k_{i}<b$ .
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Then the minimum element with the smallest index for intervals in $[0,k_{i})$ and $[k_{i},b)$ in each block $B_{i}$ is precomputed.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Such minimum elements are called as prefix min for the interval in $[0,k_{i})$ and suffix min for the interval in $[k_{i},b)$ .
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Each iteration of $k_{i}$ computes a pair of prefix min and suffix min.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Hence, the total number of prefix mins and suffix mins in a block $B_{i}$ is $2b$ .
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Since there are $n/b$ blocks, in total, all prefix min and suffix min arrays take $O(2b\cdot {n \over b})$ which is $O(n)$ spaces.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] In total, it takes $O(n)$ space to store all 3 groups of precomputed variables mentioned above.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Let $B_{i}$ be the block that contains the element at index i , and $B_{j}$ for index j .
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] All 3 questions can be answered in constant time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Hence, case 1 can be answered in linear space and constant time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] The sequence of RMQ that reduced from LCA has one property that a normal RMQ doesn’t have.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] The next element is always +1 or -1 from the current element.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Therefore, each block $B_{i}$ can be encoded as a bitstring with 0 represents the current depth -1, and 1 represent the current depth +1.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] This transformation turns a block $B_{i}$ into a bitstring of size $b-1$ .
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] A bitstring of size $b-1$ has $2^{b-1}$ possible bitstrings.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Hence, $B_{i}$ is always one of the ${\sqrt {n}}$ possible bitstring with size of $b-1$ .
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Then, for each possible bitstring, we apply the naïve quadratic space constant time solution.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Therefore, answering the $RMQ(i,j)$ query in case 2 is simply finding the corresponding block (in which is a bitstring) and perform a table lookup for that bitstring.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Hence, case 2 can be solved using linear space with constant searching time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] While originally studied in the context of trees, the notion of lowest common ancestors can be defined for directed acyclic graphs (DAGs), using either of two possible definitions.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] In both, the edges of the DAG are assumed to point from parents to children.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] In a tree, the lowest common ancestor is unique; in a DAG of n nodes, each pair of nodes may have as much as *n*-2 LCAs (Bender et al.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] 2005), while the existence of an LCA for a pair of nodes is not even guaranteed in arbitrary connected DAGs.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] A brute-force algorithm for finding lowest common ancestors is given by Aït-Kaci et al.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] (1989): find all ancestors of x and y, then return the maximum element of the intersection of the two sets.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Better algorithms exist that, analogous to the LCA algorithms on trees, preprocess a graph to enable constant-time LCA queries.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] The problem of *LCA existence* can be solved optimally for sparse DAGs by means of an O(|*V*||*E*|) algorithm due to Kowaluk & Lingas (2005).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] (2013) present a unified framework for preprocessing directed acyclic graphs to compute *a representative* lowest common ancestor in *a rooted DAG* in constant time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] Their framework can achieve near-linear preprocessing times for sparse graphs and is available for public use.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] The problem of computing lowest common ancestors of classes in an inheritance hierarchy arises in the implementation of object-oriented programming systems (Aït-Kaci et al.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/lowest-common-ancestor] The LCA problem also finds applications in models of complex systems found in distributed computing (Bender et al.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] In computer science, a **range minimum query** (**RMQ**) solves the problem of finding the minimal value in a sub-array of an array of comparable objects.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] Range minimum queries have several use cases in computer science, such as the lowest common ancestor problem and the longest common prefix problem (LCP).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] Given an array *A*[1 … *n*] of n objects taken from a totally ordered set, such as integers, the range minimum query RMQ*A*(*l*,*r*) =arg min *A*[*k*] (with 1 ≤ *l* ≤ *k* ≤ *r* ≤ *n*) returns the position of the minimal element in the specified sub-array *A*[*l* … *r*].
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] In a typical setting, the array A is static, i.e., elements are not inserted or deleted during a series of queries, and the queries to be answered on-line (i.e., the whole set of queries are not known in advance to the algorithm).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] In this case a suitable preprocessing of the array into a data structure ensures faster query answering.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] A naive solution is to precompute all possible queries, i.e. the minimum of all sub-arrays of A, and store these in an array B such that *B*[*i*, *j*] = min(*A*[*i*…*j*]); then a range min query can be solved in constant time by array lookup in B.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] There are Θ(*n*²) possible queries for a length-n array, and the answers to these can be computed in Θ(*n*²) time by dynamic programming.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] As in the solution above, answering queries in constant time will be achieved by pre-computing results.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] However, the array will store pre-computed range minimum queries not for every range [*i*, *j*], but only for ranges whose size is a power of two.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] There are O(log *n*) such queries for each start position i, so the size of the dynamic programming table B is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] After this pre-computing step, a query RMQ*A*(*l*,*r*) can now be answered in constant time by splitting it into two separate queries: one is the pre-computed query with range from l to the largest memoized value smaller than r.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] The other is the query of an interval of the same length that has r as its right boundary.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] These intervals may overlap, but since we are trying to compute the minimum rather than, for example, the sum of the numbers in the array, this does not matter.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] The overall result can thus be obtained, after the linearithmic time pre-computing, in constant time: the two queries can be answered in constant time and the only thing left to do is to choose the smaller of the two results.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] This solution does pre-computation in *O*(*n*) time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] Its data structures use *O*(*n*) space and its data structures can be used to answer queries in logarithmic time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] The array is first conceptually divided into blocks of size *s* = ⁠log *n*/4⁠.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] Then the minimum for each block can be computed in *O*(*n*) time overall and the minima are stored in a new array.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] For example, using the array *A* = [0,5,2,5,4,3,1,6,3] and a block size of 3 (for illustrative purposes only) yields the minimum array *A'* = [0,3,1].
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] Using the solution above, the sub-queries inside the blocks that are not fully contained in the query still need to be answered in constant time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] There are at most two of those blocks: the block containing l and the block containing r.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] Constant time is achieved by storing the Cartesian trees for all the blocks in the array.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] For every such tree, the possible result for all queries need to be stored.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] This comes down to *s*2 or *O*(log2 *n*) entries.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] This means the overall size of the table is *O*(*n*).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] To look up results efficiently, the Cartesian tree (row) corresponding to a specific block must be addressable in constant time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] The solution is to store the results for all trees in an array and find a unique projection from binary trees to integers to address the entries.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] This can be achieved by doing a breadth-first-search through the tree and adding leaf nodes so that every existing node in the Cartesian tree has exactly two children.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] The integer is then generated by representing every inner node as a 0-bit and every leaf as a 1-bit in a bit-word (by traversing the tree in level-order again).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] This leads to a size of ⁠log *n*/4⁠ for every tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] To enable random access in constant time to any tree, the trees not contained in the original array need to be included as well.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] An array with indices of ⁠log *n*/4⁠ bits length has size 2⁠log *n*/4⁠ = *O*(*n*).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] RMQs are used as a tool for many tasks in exact and approximate string matching.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] Several applications can be found in Fischer and Heun (2007).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] RMQs can be used to solve the lowest common ancestor problem and are used as a tool for many tasks in exact and approximate string matching.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] The LCA query LCA*S*(*v*, *w*) of a rooted tree *S* = (*V*, *E*) and two nodes *v*, *w* ∈ *V* returns the deepest node u (which may be v or w) on paths from the root to both w and v.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] Gabow, Bentley, and Tarjan (1984) showed that the LCA Problem can be reduced in linear time to the RMQ problem.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] It follows that, like the RMQ problem, the LCA problem can be solved in constant time and linear space.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] In the context of text indexing, RMQs can be used to find the LCP (longest common prefix), where LCP*T*(*i*, *j*) computes the LCP of the suffixes that start at indexes i and j in T.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] To do this we first compute the suffix array A, and the inverse suffix array *A*−1.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] We then compute the LCP array H giving the LCP of adjacent suffixes in A.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/range-minimum-query] Once these data structures are computed, and RMQ preprocessing is complete, the length of the general LCP can be computed in constant time by the formula: LCP(*i*, *j*) = RMQH(*A*-1[*i*] + 1, *A*-1[*j*]), where we assume for simplicity that *A*-1[*i*] + 1 <= *A*-1[*j*] (otherwise swap).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] In computer science, **Tarjan's off-line lowest common ancestors algorithm** is an algorithm for computing lowest common ancestors for pairs of nodes in a tree, based on the union-find data structure.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] The lowest common ancestor of two nodes *d* and *e* in a rooted tree *T* is the node *g* that is an ancestor of both *d* and *e* and that has the greatest depth in *T*.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] It is named after Robert Tarjan, who discovered the technique in 1979.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] Tarjan's algorithm is an offline algorithm; that is, unlike other lowest common ancestor algorithms, it requires that all pairs of nodes for which the lowest common ancestor is desired must be specified in advance.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] The simplest version of the algorithm uses the union-find data structure, which unlike other lowest common ancestor data structures can take more than constant time per operation when the number of pairs of nodes is similar in magnitude to the number of nodes.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] A later refinement by Gabow & Tarjan (1983) speeds the algorithm up to linear time.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] The pseudocode below determines the lowest common ancestor of each pair in *P*, given the root *r* of a tree in which the children of node *n* are in the set *n.children*.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] For this offline algorithm, the set *P* must be specified in advance.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] It uses the *MakeSet*, *Find*, and *Union* functions of a disjoint-set data structure.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] *MakeSet(u)* removes *u* to a singleton set, *Find(u)* returns the standard representative of the set containing *u*, and *Union(u,v)* merges the set containing *u* with the set containing *v*.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] TarjanOLCA(*r*) is first called on the root *r*.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] Each node is initially white, and is colored black after it and all its children have been visited.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] According to Tarjan (1979) the time complexity is O((m + n)a(m + n, n)), where m is the number of edges and n the number of vertices and a is the inverse Ackerman function, **provided** that the time to find the vertex pairs corresponding to u takes constant time per vertex.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] The paper recommends using an adjacency list (called adjacency structure in the paper).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] It is possible to preprocess the input LCA queries in such a manner, that the algorithm works faster by an order of magnitude.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tarjan-s-off-line-lowest-common-ancestors-algorithm] The idea in the optimization is associating nodes with their counterparts in the list of input queries.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] In computer science, a **tree** is a widely used abstract data type that represents a hierarchical tree structure with a set of connected nodes.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Each node in the tree can be connected to many children (depending on the type of tree), but must be connected to exactly one parent, except for the *root* node, which has no parent (i.e., the root node as the top-most node in the tree hierarchy).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] These constraints mean there are no cycles or "loops" (no node can be its own ancestor), and also that each child can be treated like the root node of its own subtree, making recursion a useful technique for tree traversal.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] In contrast to linear data structures, many trees cannot be represented by relationships between neighboring nodes (parent and children nodes of a node under consideration, if they exist) in a single straight line (called edge or link between two adjacent nodes).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Binary trees are a commonly used type, which constrain the number of children for each parent to at most two.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] When the order of the children is specified, this data structure corresponds to an ordered tree in graph theory.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] A value or pointer to other data may be associated with every node in the tree, or sometimes only with the *leaf nodes*, which have no children nodes.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] The abstract data type (ADT) can be represented in a number of ways, including a list of parents with pointers to children, a list of children with pointers to parents, or a list of nodes and a separate list of parent-child relations (a specific type of adjacency list).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Representations might also be more complicated, for example using indexes or ancestor lists for performance.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Trees as used in computing are similar to but can be different from mathematical constructs of trees in graph theory, trees in set theory, and trees in descriptive set theory.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] A node is a structure which may contain data and connections to other nodes, sometimes called **edges** or **links**.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Each node in a tree has zero or more **child nodes**, which are below it in the tree (by convention, trees are drawn with *descendants* going downwards).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] A node that has a child is called the child's **parent node** (or superior).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] All nodes have exactly one parent, except the topmost **root node**, which has none.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] A node might have many **ancestor nodes**, such as the parent's parent.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Child nodes with the same parent are **sibling nodes**.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Typically siblings have an order, with the first one conventionally drawn on the left.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Some definitions allow a tree to have no nodes at all, in which case it is called *empty*.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] An **internal node** (also known as an **inner node**, **inode** for short, or **branch node**) is any node of a tree that has child nodes.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Similarly, an **external node** (also known as an **outer node**, **leaf node**, or **terminal node**) is any node that does not have child nodes.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] The **height** of a node is the length of the longest downward path to a leaf from that node.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] The height of the root is the height of the tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] The **depth** of a node is the length of the path to its root (i.e., its *root path*).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Thus the root node has depth zero, leaf nodes have height zero, and a tree with only a single node (hence both a root and leaf) has depth and height zero.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Conventionally, an empty tree (tree with no nodes, if such are allowed) has height −1.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Each non-root node can be treated as the root node of its own **subtree**, which includes that node and all its descendants.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] A node reachable by repeated proceeding from child to parent.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] A node reachable by repeated proceeding from parent to child.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] For a given node, its number of children.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] The degree of a tree is the maximum degree of a node in the tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] The number of edges along the shortest path between two nodes.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] The level of a node is the number of edges along the unique path between it and the root node.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] A tree with every level filled, except the last.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] A rooted tree in which an ordering is specified for the children of each vertex.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Stepping through the items of a tree, by means of the connections between parents and children, is called **walking the tree**, and the action is a *walk* of the tree.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Often, an operation might be performed when a pointer arrives at a particular node.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] There are many different ways to represent trees.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] In working memory, nodes are typically dynamically allocated records with pointers to their children, their parents, or both, as well as any associated data.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] If of a fixed size, the nodes might be stored in a list.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Nodes and relationships between nodes might be stored in a separate special type of adjacency list.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] In relational databases, nodes are typically represented as table rows, with indexed row IDs facilitating pointers between parents and children.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Nodes can also be stored as items in an array, with relationships between them determined by their positions in the array (as in a binary heap).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] A binary tree can be implemented as a list of lists: the head of a list (the value of the first term) is the left child (subtree), while the tail (the list of second and subsequent terms) is the right child (subtree).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] This can be modified to allow values as well, as in Lisp S-expressions, where the head (value of first term) is the value of the node, the head of the tail (value of second term) is the left child, and the tail of the tail (list of third and subsequent terms) is the right child.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Ordered trees can be naturally encoded by finite sequences, for example with natural numbers.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] 4 has more than one parent (inbound edge).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] B has more than one parent (inbound edge).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] In terms of type theory, a tree is an inductive type defined by the constructors nil (empty forest) and node (tree with root node with given value and children).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Viewed as a whole, a tree data structure is an ordered tree, generally with values attached to each node.
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Often trees have a fixed (more properly, bounded) branching factor (outdegree), particularly always having two child nodes (possibly empty, hence *at most* two *non-empty* child nodes), hence a "binary tree".
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] Allowing empty trees makes some definitions simpler, some more complicated: a rooted tree must be non-empty, hence if empty trees are allowed the above definition instead becomes "an empty tree or a rooted tree such that ...".
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] On the other hand, empty trees simplify defining fixed branching factor: with empty trees allowed, a binary tree is a tree such that every node has exactly two children, each of which is a tree (possibly empty).
[src:lowest-common-ancestor/tree-data-structure] JSON and YAML documents can be thought of as trees, but are typically represented by nested lists and dictionaries.
